def clean_df(df):
    """
    Returns a clean data frame, for this problem.
    Takes only one parameter, the data frame.
    """
    df.columns = [col.lower().replace('-','_') for col in df.columns]
    
    # one-hot encoding all categorical variables
    cats_columns = list(df.loc[:,df.dtypes=='object'].columns)
    cats_columns = cats_columns[:-1]
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[cats_columns], drop_first=True)
    new_df = df.join(dummies)
    
    # now drop the ones that are objects and encoded
    new_df.drop(cats_columns, axis = 1, inplace = True)
    
    # change the target variable to positive/negative class
    new_df['wage'] = new_df['wage'].map(lambda x: x.strip()) # there's extra invisible space, next line won't work w/o this
    new_df['wage'] = new_df['wage'].map({'<=50K' : 0, '>50K' : 1}) 
    
    return new_df

def modeling(model, X_train = X_train, X_test = X_test, y_train=y_train, y_test = y_test):
    """
    Returns cross-validation score for quick testing. 
    Need to import all the wanted models beforehand.
    Need to run train/test/split beforehand.
    
    Parameters:
    -----------
    model: the name of the model, without parantheses. 
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test: from the cell in a cell beforehand.
    """
    
    from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
    ss = StandardScaler()
    X_train_sc = ss.fit_transform(X_train)
    X_test_sc = ss.transform(X_test)

    model = model()
    model.fit(X_train_sc, y_train)
    
    from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
    scores = cross_val_score(model, X_test, y_test, cv = 5).mean()
    
    return scores

    Returns a clean data frame, for this problem.
    Takes only one parameter, the data frame.
    """
    df.columns = [col.lower().replace('-','_') for col in df.columns]
    
    # one-hot encoding all categorical variables
    cats_columns = list(df.loc[:,df.dtypes=='object'].columns)
    
    dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[cats_columns], drop_first=True)
    new_df = df.join(dummies)
    
    # now drop the ones that are objects and encoded
    new_df.drop(cats_columns, axis = 1, inplace = True)
    
    return new_df
